Introduction

The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the most famous and popular basketball league in the United States of America. The league is a way for athletes from all over the world to gain fame, wealth and have the glory of playing basketball in the United States. The playoffs are an important way for teams to show they are the best overall, as only 16 teams are able to make the playoffs from the regular season. In this project, we will use the stats from the regular 2024-2025 season to see how well a team performs in the post season, using predictors such as point scored, rebounds, assists, three pointers made in a game, field goal percentages and amount of steals. The top 5 players, by minutes, on each playoff team will have these stats averaged between each other to see team statistics.

In[8]:
import requests
import pandas as pd
from nba_api.stats.static import teams
from nba_api.stats.endpoints import LeagueGameFinder, LeagueDashPlayerStats
import time

# NBA Team IDs
nba_team_ids = {t['id'] for t in teams.get_teams()}

# Pulling playoff games
gf = LeagueGameFinder(
    season_nullable   = '2024-25',
    season_type_nullable = 'Playoffs',
    league_id_nullable= '00'
)
games = gf.get_data_frames()[0]

# Grabbing Playoff teams
playoff_team_ids = set(games['TEAM_ID']) & nba_team_ids
assert len(playoff_team_ids) == 16

# Players per game stats
pergame = LeagueDashPlayerStats(
    season              = '2024-25',
    season_type_all_star       = 'Playoffs',
    per_mode_detailed   = 'PerGame'
).get_data_frames()[0]

# Players on playoff teams
pergame = pergame[pergame['TEAM_ID'].isin(playoff_team_ids)]

# Top 5 players by minutes on each team
top5_list = []
for tid in playoff_team_ids:
    top5 = (
        pergame[pergame['TEAM_ID'] == tid]
        .nlargest(5, 'MIN')[['PLAYER_ID','PLAYER_NAME','TEAM_ID','TEAM_ABBREVIATION']]
    )
    top5_list.append(top5)

df_top5 = pd.concat(top5_list, ignore_index=True)
player_ids_array = df_top5['PLAYER_ID'].to_numpy()

url = 'https://stats.nba.com/stats/playercareerstats'
headers = {
    'Host': 'stats.nba.com',
    'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) '
                  'AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) '
                  'Chrome/114.0.0.0 Safari/537.36',
    'Accept': 'application/json, text/plain, */*',
    'Accept-Language': 'en-US,en;q=0.9',
    'Referer': 'https://stats.nba.com/',
    'Origin': 'https://stats.nba.com',
    'Connection': 'keep-alive',
}

all_seasons = []

for pid in player_ids_array:
    params = {
        'LeagueID': '',
        'PerMode':  'PerGame',
        'PlayerID': str(pid),
    }
    resp = requests.get(url, headers=headers, params=params, timeout=10)
    resp.raise_for_status()
    rs = resp.json()['resultSets'][0]
    df = pd.DataFrame(rs['rowSet'], columns=rs['headers'])
    
    # keep only 2024-25
    df_2425 = df[df['SEASON_ID'] == '2024-25'].copy()
    df_2425['PLAYER_ID'] = pid
    all_seasons.append(df_2425)
    
    time.sleep(0.5) 

# combine players' data for 24-25
df_2425_all = pd.concat(all_seasons, ignore_index=True)

import numpy as np

# Grouping keys
group_keys = ['TEAM_ID','TEAM_ABBREVIATION']

# Search for percentage columns
pct_cols = (
    [c for c in df_2425_all.columns if c.endswith('_PCT')]
    + ['PLAYER_AGE','GP','GS','MIN']
)

# Columns to sum minues grouping keys
num_cols = df_2425_all.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
sum_cols = [c for c in num_cols if c not in pct_cols + group_keys]

# Build agg dict, without group keys
agg_dict = {c: 'sum'  for c in sum_cols}
agg_dict.update({c: 'mean' for c in pct_cols})

# Filter outTOT, TOR, and DAL rows for calculation
df_team_metrics = (
    df_2425_all
      .loc[
         (df_2425_all['TEAM_ABBREVIATION'] != 'TOT') &
         (~df_2425_all['TEAM_ABBREVIATION'].isin(['TOR','DAL', 'BKN']))
      ]
      .groupby(group_keys)
      .agg(agg_dict)
      .reset_index()
)

This scatterplot reveals a clear positive relationship between total playoff points scored by each teams top five players and their regular season win percentage. Teams with higher point totals from their core players such as Oklahoma City (OKC), Cleveland (CLE), and Boston (BOS) tend to cluster toward the upper-right quadrant, indicating both strong individual performances and high overall team success. Conversely, teams like Brooklyn (BKN) and Toronto (TOR) show both low point production from their top contributors and low win percentages, suggesting weaker offensive efficiency or depth issues. Notably, Miami (MIA) stands out as an exception: despite having a top-5 core with high playoff point totals, the teams regular season win percentage remains below average potentially due to over-reliance on a few players, poor defensive performance, or regular season injuries. The fitted regression line confirms the general trend that teams with stronger top-heavy scoring generally perform better, though variability exists, emphasizing that scoring alone is not the sole driver of team success.

For our project, we are analyzing NBA player game statistics from the 20242025 NBA season, focusing specifically on players whose teams qualified for the 2025 NBA Playoffs. Each observation in our dataset represents an individual player's performance in a single regular season game, along with several contextual features about that game. We estimate approximately 6,560 observations, based on 82 regular season games played by each of the 16 playoff teams, and data collected for the top five players on each team, as determined by total minutes played. Each observation includes roughly 15 predictor variables: 11 individual player statistics and 4 overall game features.

The dataset includes a wide range of continuous numeric variables such as points scored (PTS), rebounds (REB), assists (AST), minutes played (MIN), field goals made (FG), three-pointers made (FG3), free throws made (FT), field goal percentage (FG_PCT), three-point percentage (FG3_PCT), free throw percentage (FT_PCT), turnovers (TOV), steals (STL), blocks (BLK), and plus-minus (PLUS_MINUS), which reflects a players on-court impact. In addition, several categorical variables are included, such as game outcome (win or loss, WL). These variables provide a comprehensive view of both player performance and game context, enabling us to explore how individual regular season metrics relate to overall team success.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# Win-loss formatted strings to numeric 
df_merged[['FT_wins', 'FT_losses']] = df_merged['FewerTurnovers'].str.split('-', expand=True).astype(int)
df_merged[['LR_wins', 'LR_losses']] = df_merged['LeadInReb'].str.split('-', expand=True).astype(int)

# Win percentages
df_merged['FT_win_pct'] = df_merged['FT_wins'] / (df_merged['FT_wins'] + df_merged['FT_losses'])
df_merged['LR_win_pct'] = df_merged['LR_wins'] / (df_merged['LR_wins'] + df_merged['LR_losses'])

# Drop string columns
df_merged.drop(columns=['FewerTurnovers', 'LeadInReb', 'FT_wins', 'FT_losses', 'LR_wins', 'LR_losses'], inplace=True)

# Final predictor list
features = ['PTS', 'AST', 'FG_PCT', 'DiffPointsPG', 'FT_win_pct', 'LR_win_pct']
X = df_merged[features]
y = df_merged['WinPCT']

# Train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=134)

lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = lr.predict(X_test)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))

print("Linear Regression Results")
print("R Score:", round(r2, 4))
print("RMSE:", round(rmse, 4))

coef_table = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': features,
    'Coefficient': lr.coef_
}).sort_values(by='Coefficient', key=abs, ascending=False)

print("\n Coefficient Table:")
print(coef_table)

Our linear regression model achieved an R of 0.957 and an RMSE of 0.032, indicating a very strong fit. The most influential predictor was FT_win_pct, suggesting that teams who more consistently win the turnover battle tend to have higher win percentages. LR_win_pct (leading in rebounds) also showed a strong positive association with winning. Interestingly, while FG_PCT is often considered a key indicator of offensive efficiency, it had a negative coefficient in our model, possibly due to multicollinearity with PTS or DiffPointsPG. Overall, the model highlights the importance of possession-based metrics (turnovers, rebounds) over raw point totals or shooting percentages.

def win_loss_to_pct(series):
    return series.str.split('-').apply(lambda x: int(x[0]) / (int(x[0]) + int(x[1])) if len(x) == 2 else np.nan)

df_merged['Score100_win_pct'] = win_loss_to_pct(df_merged['Score100PTS'])
df_merged['OppScore100_win_pct'] = win_loss_to_pct(df_merged['OppScore100PTS'])


df_merged.drop(columns=['Score100PTS', 'OppScore100PTS'], inplace=True)


features = [
    'PTS', 'AST', 'FG_PCT', 'DiffPointsPG',
    'FT_win_pct', 'LR_win_pct',
    'OppPointsPG', 'TotalPoints',
    'Score100_win_pct', 'OppScore100_win_pct'
]

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd


features = [
    'PTS', 'AST', 'FG_PCT', 'DiffPointsPG',
    'FT_win_pct', 'LR_win_pct',
    'OppPointsPG', 'TotalPoints',
    'Score100_win_pct', 'OppScore100_win_pct'
]



X = df_merged[features]
y = df_merged['WinPCT']


X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=134)

# Random Forest Regressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=134)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)


def mean_squared_error_manual(y_true, y_pred):
    y_true = np.array(y_true)
    y_pred = np.array(y_pred)
    return np.mean((y_true - y_pred) ** 2)

def root_mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error_manual(y_true, y_pred))

y_pred_rf = rf.predict(X_test)
r2_rf = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
rmse_rf = root_mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_rf)


print("Random Forest Results")
print("R Score:", round(r2_rf, 4))
print("RMSE:", round(rmse_rf, 4))

importances = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': features,
    'Importance': rf.feature_importances_
}).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

print("\n Feature Importances:")
print(importances)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.barh(importances['Feature'], importances['Importance'], color='forestgreen')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.title('Random Forest Feature Importances')
plt.xlabel('Importance Score')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We trained a Random Forest Regressor to predict team win percentage (WinPCT) using a diverse set of features capturing offensive performance, defensive consistency, and game efficiency. Random Forest is particularly well-suited for this task because it can model complex, nonlinear relationships and interactions between variables that linear regression may miss. The model achieved an R score of 0.9327 and an RMSE of 0.0401, indicating strong predictive performance. While this is slightly lower in R than our linear regression model (0.9573), Random Forest offers advantages in flexibility and interpretability through feature importance rankings.

The feature importance results revealed that FT_win_pct, a proxy for winning the turnover battle, was the most important predictor of team success. This highlights the importance of ball control in postseason outcomes. Following that, OppScore100_win_pct was the second most influential feature, suggesting that teams who more consistently prevent opponents from scoring 100 or more points tend to win more games. DiffPointsPG (point differential per game) and Score100_win_pct (how often a team scores 100+ themselves) were also important, underscoring the value of both offensive power and defensive consistency.

Interestingly, traditional stats such as total points (PTS), assists (AST), and field goal percentage (FG_PCT) were among the least important features in the model. This supports the notion that raw production metrics are less predictive than efficiency- and control-based metrics when it comes to winning games. Overall, the Random Forest model suggests that possession-based performance (turnovers, rebounding) and defensive reliability are more critical for playoff success than simply scoring a lot of points.

We trained an XGBoost Regressor to predict team win percentage using the same ten features used in previous models. The model achieved an R score of 0.9071 and an RMSE of 0.0471. While its performance was slightly lower than that of linear regression and random forest, XGBoost still captured meaningful nonlinear relationships and offered insight into which features had the strongest predictive power.

Feature importance rankings showed that FT_win_pct (turnover win percentage) overwhelmingly dominated the model, accounting for more than two-thirds of the total importance. This indicates that ball control and possession efficiency are critical to team success. The second most important feature was DiffPointsPG, reinforcing the idea that consistently outscoring opponents is highly predictive of wins. Interestingly, XGBoost downweighted traditional stats such as total points, assists, and even field goal percentage, and completely ignored TotalPoints and OppPointsPG, likely because their predictive signal was already captured by more efficient summary metrics.\

Compared to the Random Forest model, XGBoost placed even more emphasis on a few select features, particularly FT_win_pct. While Random Forest distributed importance more evenly, XGBoost identified turnover advantage and scoring margin as the only features with strong predictive value. This suggests that XGBoost may be more aggressive in pruning features it finds non-informative. One limitation of the model is its complete disregard for variables like TotalPoints, which may still hold contextual value in team analysis, even if they are collinear or redundant. Nonetheless, XGBoosts ability to highlight the most decisive metrics provides clear, actionable insights.

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import numpy as np


features = [
    'PTS', 'AST', 'FG_PCT', 'DiffPointsPG',
    'FT_win_pct', 'LR_win_pct',
    'OppPointsPG', 'TotalPoints',
    'Score100_win_pct', 'OppScore100_win_pct'
]

X = df_merged[features].values
X_random_Forest = df_merged[features].values
y = df_merged['WinPCT'].values

# Normalize
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)


X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=134)


model = Sequential([
    Dense(32, activation='relu', input_shape=(X.shape[1],)),
    Dense(16, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1)  # Output layer for regression
])

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')

# Train with early stopping
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)

history = model.fit(
    X_train, y_train,
    validation_split=0.2,
    epochs=200,
    batch_size=8,
    callbacks=[early_stop],
    verbose=1
)


y_pred_nn = model.predict(X_test).flatten()
r2_nn = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_nn)
rmse_nn = root_mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_nn)

print("Neural Network Results")
print("R Score:", round(r2_nn, 4))
print("RMSE:", round(rmse_nn, 4))

We implemented a fully connected neural network to predict team win percentage using the same ten features applied in previous models. The model architecture consisted of two hidden layers (32 and 16 neurons) with ReLU activation and an output layer for regression. We used mean squared error as the loss function and trained the model with early stopping to avoid overfitting.

The model achieved an R score of 0.8748 and an RMSE of 0.0547. These results indicate that the neural network captured a substantial portion of the variance in team win percentage, although it underperformed slightly compared to linear regression, random forest, and XGBoost. The training and validation loss curves suggested good convergence and minimal overfitting, validating the effectiveness of early stopping. Additionally, the residual plot showed generally low prediction error across the test set, though a few predictions deviated modestly.

One limitation of neural networks in this context is the lack of interpretability. Unlike tree-based models, the NN does not provide feature importances, making it more difficult to understand which predictors had the greatest influence. However, the NN serves as a valuable nonlinear benchmark, offering a flexible function approximation method that complements the results of the other models in our analysis.

To evaluate which features most influenced our neural networks prediction of playoff win percentage, we conducted a one-variable sensitivity analysis. Each feature was nudged slightly while keeping all others constant, and the change in predicted win percentage was recorded.

The results revealed that OppScore100_win_pct (how often opponents scored 100+ points) had the largest positive influence. This may indicate that teams allowing opponents to score often but still winning tend to be offensively dominant. FG_PCT (field goal percentage) and LR_win_pct (rebounding win rate) also contributed positively to win prediction, reflecting offensive efficiency and control of possession.

Interestingly, AST, DiffPointsPG, and WINS had small or even negative effects in this sample, which could reflect multicollinearity or how those stats behave in combination with others. While surprising at first glance, this highlights one of the strengths of neural networks: capturing non-obvious interactions.

Overall, the sensitivity chart supports key basketball insights shooting efficiency, rebounding, and opponent containment play strong roles in playoff success while also reflecting the models flexibility in weighing features adaptively.

Overall, the neural network demonstrated strong predictive performance with an R of 0.8748, and provided deeper insight into complex relationships between team metrics and playoff success. While the model captures nonlinear interactions more flexibly than linear models, it trades off interpretability. However, our sensitivity analysis helped reveal which features most influence playoff win predictions. The neural network complements our other models by offering a more adaptive approach to evaluating NBA team strength.

from nba_api.stats.endpoints import TeamGameLogs
import pandas as pd

season = '2024-25'
logs = TeamGameLogs(season_nullable=season, season_type_nullable='Playoffs').get_data_frames()[0]
logs['WIN'] = logs['WL'] == 'W'

# Normalize series names
def normalize_series(m):
    teams = m.replace('@', '').replace('vs.', '').split()
    return " vs ".join(sorted(set(teams)))

logs['SERIES_ID'] = logs['MATCHUP'].apply(normalize_series)


# Full name to abbreviation mapping
team_name_to_abbr = {
    'Boston Celtics': 'BOS',
    'New York Knicks': 'NYK',
    'Orlando Magic': 'ORL',
    'Indiana Pacers': 'IND',
    'Cleveland Cavaliers': 'CLE',
    'Miami Heat': 'MIA',
    'Denver Nuggets': 'DEN',
    'LA Clippers': 'LAC',
    'Oklahoma City Thunder': 'OKC',
    'Detroit Pistons': 'DET',
    'Golden State Warriors': 'GSW',
    'Houston Rockets': 'HOU',
    'Minnesota Timberwolves': 'MIN',
    'Milwaukee Bucks': 'MIL',
    'Los Angeles Lakers': 'LAL',
    'Memphis Grizzlies': 'MEM'
}

def get_2025_series_results_detailed_abbr():
    # Count wins for each team in each series
    win_counts = logs.groupby(['SERIES_ID', 'TEAM_NAME'])['WIN'].sum().reset_index()

    # Aggregate into a structured list of series with team abbreviations
    series_data = []
    for series_id, group in win_counts.groupby('SERIES_ID'):
        teams = group.sort_values('WIN', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
        if len(teams) == 2:
            team1_full = teams.loc[0, 'TEAM_NAME']
            wins1 = teams.loc[0, 'WIN']
            team2_full = teams.loc[1, 'TEAM_NAME']
            wins2 = teams.loc[1, 'WIN']
            
            # Convert to abbreviations
            team1 = team_name_to_abbr.get(team1_full, team1_full)
            team2 = team_name_to_abbr.get(team2_full, team2_full)
            winner = team1 if wins1 > wins2 else team2

            series_data.append({
                'SERIES': f"{team1} vs {team2}",
                'Winner': team1,
                'WINS_1': wins1,
                'Loser': team2,
                'WINS_2': wins2,
                'WINNER': winner
            })

    return pd.DataFrame(series_data)

# Usage
series_summary = get_2025_series_results_detailed_abbr()

import random
import pandas as pd

def simulate_series_from_probs(matchups, team_probs_df, max_games=7):
    team_prob_dict = dict(zip(team_probs_df['TEAM_NAME'], team_probs_df['WIN_PROB']))
    
    results = []
    for team1, team2 in matchups:
        prob1 = team_prob_dict.get(team1, 0.5)
        prob2 = team_prob_dict.get(team2, 0.5)
        
        team1_wins = 0
        team2_wins = 0
        for game in range(max_games):
            # Normalize win probabilities
            p_total = prob1 + prob2
            p1 = prob1 / p_total
            winner = random.choices([team1, team2], weights=[p1, 1 - p1])[0]
            
            if winner == team1:
                team1_wins += 1
            else:
                team2_wins += 1
            
            if team1_wins == 4 or team2_wins == 4:
                break
        
        results.append({
            'SERIES': f"{team1} vs {team2}",
            'TEAM_1': team1,
            'TEAM_2': team2,
            'TEAM_1_WINS': team1_wins,
            'TEAM_2_WINS': team2_wins,
            'PREDICTED_WINNER': team1 if team1_wins > team2_wins else team2
        })
    
    return pd.DataFrame(results)

def extract_playoff_matchups_abbr(series_summary_df):
    matchups = []

# Here the predictions and actual results are directly compared and the incorrect predictions are printed
def compare_predictions(most_common_df, series_summary):
    predicted_winners = most_common_df['PREDICTED_WINNER'].tolist()
    actual_winners = series_summary['WINNER'].tolist()

    correct = 0
    total = len(actual_winners)
    mismatches = []

    for i in range(total):
        predicted = predicted_winners[i] if i < len(predicted_winners) else 'N/A'
        actual = actual_winners[i]
        if predicted == actual:
            correct += 1
        else:
            mismatches.append({
                'Index': i,
                'Series': series_summary.iloc[i]['SERIES'],
                'Predicted': predicted,
                'Actual': actual
            })

    print(f"\n Correct Predictions: {correct}/{total} ({(correct / total) * 100:.1f}%)")

    if mismatches:
        print("Mismatches:")
        for m in mismatches:
            print(f"{m['Index']}: {m['Series']} -> Predicted: {m['Predicted']}, Actual: {m['Actual']}")
compare_predictions(most_common_df, series_summary)

Conclusion

The model was able to correctly predict 2 of the 4 conference finalists, that being IND and OKC, and the eventual champion if OKC wins the championship. Only 10 out of the 15 predictions were correct which gave a percentage of about 66.7. The missclassifications often invovlved close matchups such as, DEN vs LAC or MIN vs LAL, which showed that win probabilities near 50% made series very hard to predict. Because the model only used the regular season stats, it was not able to grasp the full scale of the playoffs and different events that occurred. Our model could not fully take into account roster changes, injuries and resting time for star players, coaching adjustments, intensity of playoffs as well as matchup-dependent play and most importantly, the inherent unpredictability of sports. A way that could have made the model stronger would be to analyze probability of injury for the players, or see how often players were rested, as it would have allowed for the model to see how a players availability affected the playoff performance. Overall, the model was fairly accurate at predicting playoffs, with some key differences between the predicted and actual outcome based on what predictors were used.
